Public and media access to the videoconference is available by clicking on the link posted on the district‚Äôs website at https://www.ocknights.org/

As this board meeting will be held by videoconference, and no quorum of the Board of Education will be physically present together, there will be no in-person attendance available to the public or the media. Superintendent Smith will read the public comment out loud to the board members during the ZOOM meeting. post_text: ‚Ä¢ Senior Artist Spotlight ‚Ä¢ Congratulations Jess DeLeon Guerrero! ‚ÄúMy art has always been a way for me to express myself without using words. I've always hesitated to make art that represented myself or my background because I'm so different. I separated the style of my personal art from the style for my projects that I would showcase, but my teachers and friends loved the art that I kept to myself. So I became more comfortable with making art that I want, and my results were better than I expected. I would say art made me acknowledge my differences because I learned to realize they make my art unique.‚Äù

Notice is hereby given that a meeting of the Board of Education of the School District of Oakland-Craig, in the County of Burt, in the State of Nebraska, a/k/a School District No. 014, has been scheduled on May 11, 2020 at 8:00 p.m. by videoconference. Public and media access to the videoconference is available by clicking on the link posted on the district‚Äôs website at https://www.ocknights.org/

As this board meeting will be held by videoconference, and no quorum of the Board of Education will be physically present together, there will be no in-person attendance available to the public or the media. Patrons that wish to provide public comment may email Superintendent Jeff Smith (jsmith@ocknights.org). Superintendent Smith will read the public comment out loud to the board members during the ZOOM meeting. A copy of the agenda, kept continuously current, is available for public inspection in the office of the Superintendent of Schools in Oakland, Nebraska, and online at the above-mentioned link.

post_text: ‚Ä¢Senior Artist Spotlight‚Ä¢ We celebrate you Aliyah Tiedtke! "I've really let my creativity fly this year. I got to experience mediums I'd never used before, and did projects I wouldn't ordinarily do at home. I used to think realism wasn't for me, but I've learned to stop letting self doubt hold me back and to just try my best. It's okay to make mistakes, because that is what makes art unique. We aren't printers. We're humans."

post_text: ‚ÄúI learned that most of the time your idea of your end result doesn't always end up how you pictured it. There are lots of bumps that you have to get over in order to get your art how you want it, and sometimes those bumps lead you into different paths to different end results. This art work has helped me grow to be less one-minded and more open-minded to different ideas and paths I can take in any situations of my life.‚Äù -Senior Megan Bousquet
